Date: Mon, 19 Dec 2011 01:03:36 -0500

 10 hours ago, Robby Findler wrote:
 > You're suggesting that shift-enter and shift-return do what
 > alt-return and control-return and enter currently do, and have
 > return and enter do what return currently does? What about
 > alt-return and control-return?
 
 I think that there might be some confusion, possibly different
 bindings due to different OSs.  (Also because what I thought that
 S-enter is doing seems wrong -- it works like plain enter for me.)
 
 What I see now is:
 
 1. Enter: enters an expression if sexpr is terminated and cursor at
    its end, newline+indent otherwise.
 
 2. C-enter: always enters what was typed, even if non-terminated or
    not at the end.
 
 3. Return (the key on the numeric keypad): always inserts a newline,
    no indentation.
 
 * S-enter and M-enter (and ESC enter) all work the same as a plain
   enter, AFAICT.
 
 The confusing thing that I referred to earlier is what return is
 doing, since I hit that every once in a while and expect it to be the
 same as enter.  I think that to minimize confusion, they should be
 exactly the same, including modifiers -- so either enter or return
 will do #1, with control they'll both do #2, and with shift they'll
 both do #3.
 
 -- 
