 > In all cases above, optionally allow "alt" (so alt-return is
 > behavior 1, alt-control-enter is behavior 2, etc)
 
 To clarify: you mean that the above bindings effectively ignore the
 alt modifier, right?  (I see no use for that, but no harm either.)
 
 
 > in case we're on a platform where "enter" is the same thing as
 > pressing "alt return".
 
 So there are keyboards where you can't do alt-<one-of-them>?  That
 would be a good point in favor of ignoring the alt modifier...
 
 
 > Does that sound right?
 
 Yes, I think that's all fine.
 
 
